Immigration enforcement became the main laboratory for this new alignment of power. The administration had already fired more than 100 immigration judges and replaced them with 600 military lawyers, many lacking deep experience in immigration law. That change turned a civilian court system into something closer to an extension of the chain of command. In the same week, ICE deported long-settled south-east Asian refugees with old convictions, sent dozens of Iranians back to Tehran under a new deal, and removed a Salvadoran journalist, Mario Guevara, after he covered a protest in Atlanta. Guevara\'92s charges had been dismissed, and he had a work permit and American children, but his case was reopened and he spent 100 days in custody before being deported. The message to immigrants and to the press was stark. Status and speech could both be grounds for removal.\
