Chicago saw the most visible expression of this approach. Under the banner of \'93Operation Midway Blitz,\'94 federal agents in military-style gear raided an apartment building, zip-tying residents and leaving families, including children, outside for hours. At the Broadview immigration processing center, protesters blocking government vehicles were met with tear gas and pepper balls. ICE agents allegedly assaulted journalists at a New York immigration court, hospitalizing one reporter. A US citizen from Alabama, detained twice despite showing identification, filed suit over warrantless raids. In each case, the line between law enforcement and intimidation blurred. Protesters, residents, and reporters were treated less as rights-bearing citizens than as obstacles to be cleared.\
