Courts did not stand aside entirely. A Reagan-appointed federal judge, William Young, ruled that the administration\'92s efforts to detain and deport foreign scholars and legal residents for pro-Palestinian speech violated the First Amendment, stressing that non-citizens share the same free-speech rights as citizens. Another judge blocked the reallocation of FEMA disaster funds from twelve states, calling the administration\'92s approach an attempt to \'93do what it wants rather than follow the law.\'94 A separate ruling stripped Trump\'92s acting US attorney in Nevada of authority for serving unlawfully. And the Supreme Court, while granting an emergency stay that allowed the administration to proceed with ending Temporary Protected Status for Venezuelan and Haitian nationals, also refused\'97for now\'97to let Trump remove Federal Reserve Governor Lisa Cook, preserving a measure of central bank independence. The judiciary was a battleground, not a monolith.\
